06:35.440 --> 06:37.060
And here are your hosts.

06:41.040 --> 06:50.520
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. Jo Clayton's Diadem series comprises seven
novels so far. These are Diadem from the Stars, Lamarchos, Irsud, Maeve, Star

06:50.520 --> 06:58.440
Hunters, The Nowhere Hunt, and Ghosthunt. Clayton's settings are well done. The
action is exciting, and her characters are deep and believable. In fact, the

06:58.440 --> 07:06.020
series is carried by the protagonist, Aleytys, who is on a quest to uncover her
heritage. We were curious how the series got started. Did Clayton conceive of

07:06.020 --> 07:21.940
Aleytys or the Diadem first? Well, Aleytys is the character, first of all.
Actually, the first image that hit me was that first page of the first book. I

07:21.940 --> 07:31.580
just got this feeling for something suddenly and breaking

07:31.580 --> 07:45.840
into the world that she knew. The crash of the ship of the thief. He was also
one of the first characters I came up with. I could see him in his flight. Well,

07:46.000 --> 07:57.500
I see these things. You know, once I get to know them, I'm a very visual person.
There's this little movie screen in the front of my head that goes through. But

07:57.500 --> 08:09.960
those are the things that came first of all. The picture of the thief in flight.
I didn't know what he had stolen. The crashing on the world. I didn't know what

08:09.960 --> 08:17.380
that crash meant. And slowly building up complications. I like complications.

08:27.900 --> 08:35.460
When one reads the Diadem series sequentially, he sees the continuing
evolution of Clayton's writing style. Yes. For instance, the first novel

08:35.460 --> 08:42.400
carefully explains the concept of the Diadem, the alien artifact containing
three trapped human spirits. It also covers how Aleytys learn to draw power

08:42.400 --> 08:52.320
from it. But in the later novels, the Diadem more or less takes a back seat to
other issues. Here Clayton comments. I also am thinking of the series as my

08:52.320 --> 09:04.080
workshop education in writing. And the concepts I might have had in the
beginning, I'm not going to stick with them. I'll modify them as necessary as I

09:04.080 --> 09:06.180
learn more about my craft.

09:11.100 --> 09:21.640
More and more, in the last books, I hope, the character of the people who are
trapped in the Diadem is coming through. And as they come out,

09:25.000 --> 09:36.820
achieve re-embodied, or whatever you want to call it, they become more and more
real to me, and more important than the Diadem itself. Aleytys is a very tough,

09:36.960 --> 09:43.660
strong character. This happened partly because of Clayton's experience in
dealing with teenagers as a teacher. She consequently had to place Aleytys in

09:43.660 --> 09:52.460
situations where even her powers would be tested. I said before that I was in a
situation where I was really banging my head against the wall. I was teaching

09:52.460 --> 10:02.120
English, you know, and while this is very important, there were so many things
happening to my kids. I guess I got too involved with them. That I was totally

10:02.120 --> 10:17.360
helpless to alleviate things that, you know, the pressures on them, the wounds
that they got from the world around them, that I was just absolutely useless in

10:17.360 --> 10:33.680
helping them live through. Only I created perhaps a character that was, in the
end, a little bit too powerful, too able to go to, well, magic her way out of

10:33.680 --> 10:43.840
things. So I had to recreate problems for her and help her come to an
understanding of the limitations of power, which I guess is one of the themes

10:43.840 --> 10:51.640
in, if there are themes in what I'm writing. More on our next show with Jo
Clayton.

