11:55.000 --> 11:58.940
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

12:14.840 --> 12:20.300
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

12:22.980 --> 12:24.720
And here are your hosts.

12:28.900 --> 12:36.780
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Jo Clayton has written seven science
fiction novels in the Diadem series. She has plans for writing two more. But

12:36.780 --> 12:43.940
Clayton has also written two novels so far in the Duel of Sorcery series, which
is fantasy. These novels are Moongather and Moonscatter. We asked Clayton why

12:43.940 --> 12:53.340
she decided to write fantasy amidst writing all that science fiction. Here she
tells us about the rather unique source of inspiration. Oh? There's a cockroach

12:53.340 --> 12:57.880
sat down beside me one day. That is the literal truth.

13:00.780 --> 13:10.000
It's one of these huge ones, about three inches long. I'm sitting, you know, I
told you I lived in this little place, little old shotgun apartment above a

13:10.000 --> 13:20.220
private house, and I'm sitting on the steps waiting for the mailman to come.
It's the thing I do, you know, writers do. And this cockroach came crawling down

13:20.220 --> 13:30.780
the side of the house, and it sat there and it looked at me. And, you know, your
first reaction with a cockroach is smash it. But I decided just to sit there and

13:30.780 --> 13:42.840
look at it, and it's a really disgusting little creature. Actually, it's kind of
pretty in its way. Very nice lines, very bright black eyes. We looked alert. And

13:42.840 --> 13:52.120
it just sat there, and we looked at each other for a while. And so I decided to
write a story about a cockroach, and I decided that it was going to be fantasy.

13:54.220 --> 14:09.160
It just seemed to fit in fantasy. So that cockroach ended up, I believe, with
about maybe 10 pages out of 300 or something like that. But he was in there. He

14:09.160 --> 14:20.080
was my inspiration. And, I don't know, it just felt like a writing fantasy. It
wasn't any great and momentous decision. It's just the way it turned out.

14:45.120 --> 14:51.880
The Cockroach Passage, by the way, is in the first novel in the series,
Moongather. Sometimes fantasy is criticized as being someone easier to write

14:51.880 --> 14:59.020
than science fiction because there are no rules to break. Right. Science fiction
takes place in a world with consistent logic, whereas in fantasy one can resort

14:59.020 --> 15:05.680
to magic when things appear hopeless. If clumsily handled, such antics can
irritate the reader. Clayton told us, though, that she believes well-written

15:05.680 --> 15:22.700
fantasy follows rules. I am one of those who really believes that there are
rules to magic. I don't believe in magic at all, but it's fun to play with.

15:22.700 --> 15:40.340
It's, I don't know, it's sort of an extension of the psionics, which is
probably, at present, is not a science either. Might be, but many people are

15:40.340 --> 15:46.300
skeptical about that. But I can't,

15:46.440 --> 15:58.460
it is just the same thing in a sense as writing science fiction, only you write
in other

15:58.460 --> 16:02.540
terms the same kind of rule keeping.

16:05.580 --> 16:12.700
And the societies, you

16:12.700 --> 16:30.320
can play with visual things and possibilities in a different way. It's not more
loose than science fiction if you do it properly, I think. It just has a

16:30.320 --> 16:41.820
different set of assumptions. And it's fun to play with those assumptions. So,
fantasy or science fiction? Jo Clayton's carefully crafted work is worth

16:41.820 --> 16:42.120
reading.

