17:49.120 --> 17:53.120
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

18:09.080 --> 18:14.520
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

18:17.220 --> 18:18.960
And here are your hosts.

18:23.380 --> 18:30.800
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon. Science fiction is a genre which invites
writers to use a wide variety of writing styles. One writer who recently emerged

18:30.800 --> 18:38.680
with a very distinctive style is Ann Maxwell, whose first novel, Change, was
published in 1975. We asked Maxwell how she decided to become a writer.

19:07.260 --> 19:13.400
My husband was working overnight as a reporter in Riverside, California. So I
decided that I would write with myself, and that's what I did. Maxwell's multi

19:13.400 --> 19:21.700
-layered, complex style is best seen in her series of four loosely connected
novels, The Singer Enigma, A Dead God Dancing, Name of a Shadow, and Jaws of

19:21.700 --> 19:29.120
Menx. Set in the far future, these novels feature a common known universe
governed by a body called the Concord. The novels don't share common characters,

19:29.160 --> 19:38.860
though. We wondered if Maxwell anticipated writing a series when she began the
first novel, The Singer Enigma. I decided that it had been fun to write a book

19:38.860 --> 19:50.460
with Earth as a base for a first book. But I was, I truly wanted the freedom
that would come from not having the Earth as we know it now in the book. And

19:50.460 --> 19:58.660
therefore I had to invent a system. And systems do, you know, people do tend
toward hierarchy and governments. And so I thought about those sorts of things

19:58.660 --> 20:07.380
for a while until I created a framework within which I could create

20:07.380 --> 20:13.600
different cultures that would yet be comprehensible

20:13.600 --> 20:24.180
through the larger framework, in this case of Concord. It was a great deal of
fun, a great intellectual play to sit there and try to figure out how people who

20:24.180 --> 20:35.180
are radically different might find ways to get along. And that in essence was
what the Concord was, the soul restraint against undeclared war, that sort of

20:35.180 --> 20:44.420
thing. I at that time did not envision writing a series with continuing
characters, but I did envision writing more books within that universe. Maxwell

20:44.420 --> 20:52.140
treats male-female relationships in great depth, not only in this series, but in
her other works, both in science fiction and out. All her novels feature

20:52.140 --> 21:03.100
relationships between men and women of strong character. Hear Maxwell comments.
Yes, it always has. I think that two strong people, a man and a woman, together

21:03.100 --> 21:07.900
can create possibilities

21:07.900 --> 21:18.340
that neither alone would have. This is not two weak people holding each other
up. This is two strong people using relationships as a springboard to other

21:18.340 --> 21:31.620
things. And yes, this is such a deeply held belief on my part that it's sort of
like pointing out that there's oxygen in the air to me. Now, I know other people

21:31.620 --> 21:40.420
don't see life like that. This is simply one of my beliefs. And it is
ineradicable. It appears in all of my books, no matter what they are. This

21:40.420 --> 21:47.760
series also features telepathic communications among various characters. An
interesting mechanical point is that the telepathic conversations are punctuated

21:47.760 --> 21:56.240
with asterisks, rather than with italics or quotation marks, except in the last
novel, The Jaws of Menx. We asked Maxwell if this was her publisher's idea. Oh,

21:56.340 --> 22:05.620
I wanted to do that. In fact, I did that up until Cigna NIL. And then Jaws of
Menx came out, and it was italicized instead of asterisk, which came as a

22:05.620 --> 22:16.580
surprise to me, because it was submitted in asterisk. And at that point, there
was no way to object. It was a style change made by the house. My contracts and

22:16.580 --> 22:24.580
I leave, and I see all such changes before they occur. But at that point, you
know, I have stuck with it, because it is the style of the house and the break

22:24.580 --> 22:37.120
that's made. But I did resent, in a way, losing the ability to italicize for
emphasis, because you can't use that for telepathy and emphasis, at least not

22:37.120 --> 22:44.500
very often, and not get away with it without confusing the reader. That's why I
chose the asterisk in the first place, to give me greater freedom. We'll have

22:44.500 --> 22:46.000
more with Anne Maxwell on our next show.

